<DOC><DOCNO> AP890719-0286 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-19-89 1714EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-19 0500</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0520</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD><BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices responded to upbeat news oninflation Wednesday with a strong rally that carried the market tonew highs since the crash of 1987.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 39.65 to 2,584.41,stretching its gain since the start of the month to 144.35 points.   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 2 to 1 innationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with1,058 up, 458 down and 495 unchanged.   Volume on the floor of the Big Board reached 215.74 millionshares, up from 152.35 million Tuesday and the heaviest total since244.51 million were traded on June 16.   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, includingtrades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in theover-the-counter market, totaled 252.14 million shares.   The Labor Department reported Wednesday morning that the consumerprice index rose 0.2 percent in June, down from 0.6 percent themonth before. The consensus estimate on Wall Street had called for a0.3 percent June increase.   Though the latest figure came as no dramatic surprise, analystssaid, it bolstered hopes that the Federal Reserve might soon relaxits credit policy further.   The news helped push interest rates lower in the governmentsecurities market today. Prices of long-term Treasury bonds, whichmove in the opposite direction from interest rates, rose about $5for each $1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.15percent-8.17 percent range.   Philip Morris, which reported sharply higher earnings for thesecond quarter, climbed 3 to 147.   Other gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up2 at 56\; American Telephone andamp; Telegraph, up ] at 36~; Exxon, up ~at 46[; McDonald's, up } at 30}, and Procter andamp; Gamble 3[ to 117[.   Pollution-control and waste-management stocks were especiallystrong, benefiting from recent bullish views on the Street about theoutlook for environmental cleanup and protection efforts. WasteManagement picked up 2] to 57~; Browning-Ferris Industries 1} to38~, and Rollins Environmental } to 11[.   Tandem Computers gained 1| to 19{ in active trading. The companyreported per-share earnings for its latest fiscal quarter of 31cents, compared to 18 cents in the comparable period a year earlier.   On the downside, McDonnell Douglas dropped 5] to 72 as thecompany posted a $48 million loss for the second quarter.   Snap-On Tools, which reported lower second-quarter profits, tooka 3|-point tumble to 36.   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000actively traded stocks, the market increased $36.05 billion, or 1.11percent, in value.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained2.19 to 187.10.   Standard andamp; Poor's industrial index rose 5.49 to 384.22, and Sandamp;P's500-stock composite index was up 4.38 at 335.73.   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained3.37 to 451.23. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex closed at 372.40, up 2.23.</TEXT></DOC>